To insert a new node with a given value (`new_value`) at the end of a singly linked list in C, you need to create a new node with the `new_value`, allocate memory for it, and then update the 'next' pointer of the last existing node to point to the new node. Here is an example:

```c
struct Node {
    int value;
    struct Node* next;
};

void insertAtEnd(struct Node** head_ref, int new_value) {
    struct Node* new_node = (struct Node*) malloc(sizeof(struct Node));
    new_node->value = new_value;
    new_node->next = NULL;

    if (*head_ref == NULL) {
        *head_ref = new_node;
        return;
    }

    struct Node* last = *head_ref;
    while (last->next != NULL)
        last = last->next;

    last->next = new_node;
}
```
